Paris was...different.  thats all i can say.  i think i've been to so many cities i'm jaded to the whole traveling thing.  its a different city, with its own perks, its own pitfalls (x-ref: lack of pooper scooper laws and keyboards specifically designed to fuck over americans), its own sights, and its own sounds.  the sights did look a tad familiar though, st. petersburg being modelled after it and everything (that and washington tends to employ some of its architecture).  rather odd though, it all looks very home-ish.  my brother and i were thrown the first few days by the fact that everything seemed sort of familiar, and the people looked like they were from here, but we'd pass them in the street and they'd be speaking their crazy moon-language.  that would snap us back to reality and we'd realize we weren't in kansas anymore (and we havent ever been to kansas, either)

total expenses paid by ryan in paris: $0.  i like this game of conserving money.

in all honesty, i would rather have been home sooner than i was, or will be, at any rate.  i've missed so much, i'm still missing a lot.  things are going to be pretty disorienting in the next week.

so we get back to union station, load up the car (my car, by the way, more on that later), and try to start it.  it wakes the whir-ing sound, but doesnt roll over.  well shit.  try again.  nope.  nothing.  usually this happens if its cold out, but seeing as it has been baking in the sun for 3 days, its unexplainable.  so after 30 minutes of fiddling, we decide to call AAA.  as soon as my mom dials the number, the engine starts.  well, sort of.  it gives a jump, makes like its about to start, then doesnt.  so we wait five minutes and try it again.  finally beat the car into submission.  then came the fun of driving it home. it ran a little funnily, even i could tell and i wasn't driving.   constantly worried that it was about to die.  but, we made it to the exxon okay.

anyways, after some deliberation, my dad and i have come to the agreement that i dont really need a new car.  the explorer is already paid for and can haul lots and lots of wood (and people).  so, the explorer is now mine officially.  it shall be cleansed of whatever crap my parents used to keep in there and will now store a sweet 125 pc tool kit i got for 60 bucks (12 volt drill though is a little weak).  in the middle of making it home today, i realised that i hadn't named it.  now, any good pirate, or sailor for that matter, knows that sailing on an unnamed ship is bad luck.  at first i thought andrea doria, but that didnt have the ring to it i wanted, nor the sort of irony i was looking for.  so, i stuck to the most familiar, warm sounding, and funny (not funny sounding, just naming it such makes me laugh) name i could.  so i channeled the spirit of my old car into the new one, and she is now named Mary Celeste II.  shes much bigger than the old sunbird-class clipper (as stated, shes an explorer-class galleon), and will likely do better should she ever go through a fight similar to the one that ended Mary Celeste I.

i realized today, i'm not afraid of death.  instead, i'm worried that i wont have a say in it.  i step out into the road with cars rushing by, not because i want to seem all tough or cool, its because i don't care.  i step out there not to prove anything, i do it because i believe i am in firm control of my fate.  i can stare at a car rushing towards me, entirely capable of sending me to the next world without fear that it will actually happen.  i've known for a long time how i will die.  i will die because i will do something stupid, and i will die fighting, i will be on plan b, the last resort, and fight till they kill me.  that's what i'm most afraid of about death, not fighting till the end.  i refuse to go quietly and without taking something or someone with me.  but i can accept my death.  i can do these things that could very well kill me and not be afraid because i don't plan on dying that day.  not yet.  so dont be scared for me, i still plan on living for a while.

so a funny thing happened today during lunch.  matt and i were throwing around a frisbee down a stretch of hallway.  i do a toss and it gains some more altitude than i intended, bumping the ceiling.  now, the exact moment it touched the ceiling (a blank tile by the way), the power went out.  now, before you say anything, i can firmly state that we did not do it.  you see, blank tiles have nothing on them, and tapping one with a frisbee wont make it jump the 6 inches into the air it would actually need to hit anything vaguely important.  besides, there is no way in hell that a vital system, something connected in series with the rest of the school's power, would a) be that sensitive and b) exist.  so all you people blaming us, fuck off.  the school is actually just that crappy.  aparantly, a tree fell on a transformer the other day, and the one they gave us is shit.

oh, and honestly, kidding me about stuff you know pisses me off (a good hint that im annoyed is when i say fuck off and walk away never to return becasue everyone is being an ass), like how i hurt my finger, or that my hair is indeed blue(ish), just pisses me off even more.  i dont care if you do it lovingly.  im tired of it.  my patience with everyone is dwindling, and as some of you have realized, im snapping at people more and more often.  so please, dont aggravate me.  (psst, hey, this means dont go around lovingly joking tomorrow saying that i caused the power to go out.  i might just sandblast the curb with your teeth.  i let you know what happened because i thought it was a hell of a coincidence.  i put in the defending statements, not to try and cover my ass, mearly to show how you would have to be a moron to seriously think we caused the power outage).
